<header class="hero">
  <div class="page">
    <div class="kicker smallcaps">Financial model review · 2026–2030 · all figures USD</div>
    <h1>A model that <span class="ital rust">adds up</span> — riding one very steep curve.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      The revised <em>Pessimistic ION Financial Model</em> is structurally sound and
      mechanically correct: balance sheets tie to zero, interest and tax-loss logic
      are properly wired. The risk lives entirely in the <em>assumptions</em> — a GMV
      ramp from $4M to $4&nbsp;billion in four years, carried by a 200× order surge and
      40%&nbsp;month-on-month compounding.
    </p>
    <div id="verdict" class="verdict">
      <div class="v"><div class="l smallcaps">Structure</div><div class="b"><span class="tag-good">Sound.</span> 3-statement linkage, balance checks at zero.</div></div>
      <div class="v"><div class="l smallcaps">Mechanics</div><div class="b"><span class="tag-good">Correct.</span> NOL, D&amp;A roll, interest on opening cash.</div></div>
      <div class="v"><div class="l smallcaps">Assumptions</div><div class="b"><span class="tag-warn">Aggressive.</span> GMV growth & take rate need support.</div></div>
      <div class="v"><div class="l smallcaps">Sensitivity tab</div><div class="b"><span class="tag-warn">Broken.</span> Downside revenue hardcoded above base.</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</header>

<section id="dashboard">
  <div class="page">
    <div class="head"><span class="num">01</span><span class="tag">The base case at a glance</span></div>
    <h2>Five years, <span class="ital">one hundred million raised.</span></h2>
    <p class="standfirst">
      $20M of equity in 2026 and $80M in 2027 fund a build-then-scale plan. The company
      burns through 2027, crosses into operating profit in 2028, and ends 2030 with
      $4.0B of annual GMV, $52M of operating revenue, and $78M of cash still on hand.
    </p>

    <div class="cards">
      <div class="mc"><div class="l smallcaps">2030 GMV</div><div class="big">$4.04B</div><div class="sub">from $4.06M in 2026</div></div>
      <div class="mc"><div class="l smallcaps">2030 Operating rev.</div><div class="big">$52.4M</div><div class="sub">+ $3.5M interest income</div></div>
      <div class="mc pos"><div class="l smallcaps">2030 EBITDA</div><div class="big">$12.1M</div><div class="sub">21.6% margin</div></div>
      <div class="mc pos"><div class="l smallcaps">Net income 2030</div><div class="big">$7.5M</div><div class="sub">positive since 2028</div></div>
      <div class="mc"><div class="l smallcaps">Cash raised</div><div class="big">$100M</div><div class="sub">all equity</div></div>
      <div class="mc"><div class="l smallcaps">2030 Cash</div><div class="big">$78.4M</div><div class="sub">never goes negative</div></div>
    </div>

    <div class="tw" style="margin-top:26px">
      <table>
        <caption>Dashboard — base case, USD millions unless stated. Source: workbook <span class="mono">Dashboard / P&amp;L / Cash Flow</span> tabs.</caption>
        <thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th class="num">2026</th><th class="num">2027</th><th class="num">2028</th><th class="num">2029</th><th class="num">2030</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>GMV ($M)</td><td class="num">4.1</td><td class="num">356.6</td><td class="num">2,114.1</td><td class="num">2,964.6</td><td class="num">4,037.8</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Total income ($M)</td><td class="num">0.5</td><td class="num">7.4</td><td class="num">35.4</td><td class="num">44.7</td><td class="num">55.9</td></tr>
          <tr><td>EBITDA ($M)</td><td class="num tneg">(8.7)</td><td class="num tneg">(13.0)</td><td class="num tpos">5.0</td><td class="num tpos">7.0</td><td class="num tpos">12.1</td></tr>
          <tr><td>EBITDA margin</td><td class="num tneg">n/m</td><td class="num tneg">(177%)</td><td class="num">14.2%</td><td class="num">15.7%</td><td class="num">21.6%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Net income ($M)</td><td class="num tneg">(9.3)</td><td class="num tneg">(15.0)</td><td class="num tpos">2.0</td><td class="num tpos">3.0</td><td class="num tpos">7.5</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Income tax ($M)</td><td class="num">0.0</td><td class="num">0.0</td><td class="num">0.0</td><td class="num">0.0</td><td class="num">0.0</td></tr>
          <tr class="total"><td>Closing cash ($M)</td><td class="num">9.0</td><td class="num">69.4</td><td class="num">67.9</td><td class="num">69.8</td><td class="num">78.4</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Balance check</td><td class="num">0</td><td class="num">0</td><td class="num">0</td><td class="num">0</td><td class="num">0</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="gmv">
  <div class="page">
    <div class="head"><span class="num">02</span><span class="tag">The load-bearing assumption</span></div>
    <h2>Everything rests on the <span class="ital rust">order ramp.</span></h2>
    <p class="standfirst">
      GMV is built bottom-up: monthly orders × average order value. Orders start at
      5,000/month in Sep-26, hit 1,000,000/month by Mar-27 (a 200× climb in seven
      months), then compound at 40% month-on-month through end-2027 before the growth
      rate steps down to 3.0%, 2.75% and 2.5% in the following years.
    </p>

    <div class="two">
      <figure class="chart">
        <div class="ctitle">Orders per month — full ramp</div>
        <div class="cnote">Sep-26 → Dec-30. Log-shaped explosion in 2027 dominates.</div>
        <svg id="chOrders" viewBox="0 0 560 280" preserveAspectRatio="none" aria-label="Orders per month"></svg>
        <div class="legend"><span><i style="background:var(--teal)"></i>orders / month (millions)</span></div>
      </figure>
      <figure class="chart">
        <div class="ctitle">Annual GMV ($M, log scale)</div>
        <div class="cnote">$4M → $4.0B. A ~1,000× jump over four years.</div>
        <svg id="chGmv" viewBox="0 0 560 280" aria-label="Annual GMV"></svg>
        <div class="legend"><span><i style="background:var(--rust)"></i>annual GMV ($M)</span></div>
      </figure>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="ct">Reviewer flag — &ldquo;too steep without adoption proof&rdquo;</div>
      <p>The model author (Kafeel) explicitly calls the trajectory aggressive: 1M orders/month
      by Mar-27 and 40% MoM growth do not reflect MSME onboarding friction, activation rates,
      or regional rollout in Indonesia. By Dec-27 the curve implies 20.7M orders/month — and
      annual orders leap from 1.0M (2026) to 71M (2027) to 577M (2030). This single driver is
      the difference between a credible plan and slideware.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="revenue">
  <div class="page">
    <div class="head"><span class="num">03</span><span class="tag">How the money is made</span></div>
    <h2>A thin fee on a <span class="ital">huge base.</span></h2>
    <p class="standfirst">
      No network fee is charged in 2026; monetization begins in 2027. The blended take
      rate is a tiered fee — 25% of GMV at tier&nbsp;1, 25% at tier&nbsp;2, 50% at
      tier&nbsp;3 — and it <em>declines</em> each year as the higher tiers are cut to stay
      competitive: 1.375% → 0.975% by 2030. Network fees plus value-added services and
      compliance support make up operating revenue; interest on idle cash tops it off.
    </p>

    <div class="two">
      <figure class="chart">
        <div class="ctitle">Operating revenue composition ($M)</div>
        <div class="cnote">Network fee dominates as GMV scales; interest income shown separately.</div>
        <svg id="chRev" viewBox="0 0 560 300" aria-label="Revenue composition"></svg>
        <div class="legend">
          <span><i style="background:var(--teal)"></i>network fee</span>
          <span><i style="background:var(--moss)"></i>value-added svc</span>
          <span><i style="background:var(--amber)"></i>compliance</span>
          <span><i style="background:var(--line)"></i>interest income</span>
        </div>
      </figure>
      <figure class="chart">
        <div class="ctitle">Blended take rate vs GMV</div>
        <div class="cnote">Take rate erodes even as GMV explodes — fee compression is built in.</div>
        <svg id="chTake" viewBox="0 0 560 300" aria-label="Take rate vs GMV"></svg>
        <div class="legend">
          <span><i style="background:var(--rust)"></i>blended fee %</span>
          <span><i style="background:var(--line)"></i>GMV ($M, area)</span>
        </div>
      </figure>
    </div>

    <div class="tw" style="margin-top:26px">
      <table>
        <caption>Revenue build — USD millions. Source: workbook <span class="mono">Revenue</span> tab.</caption>
        <thead><tr><th>Revenue line</th><th class="num">2026</th><th class="num">2027</th><th class="num">2028</th><th class="num">2029</th><th class="num">2030</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Annual GMV ($M)</td><td class="num">4.1</td><td class="num">356.6</td><td class="num">2,114.1</td><td class="num">2,964.6</td><td class="num">4,037.8</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Blended fee</td><td class="num">0.00%</td><td class="num">1.375%</td><td class="num">1.275%</td><td class="num">1.125%</td><td class="num">0.975%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Network fee revenue</td><td class="num">0.0</td><td class="num">4.9</td><td class="num">27.0</td><td class="num">33.4</td><td class="num">39.4</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Value-added service fee</td><td class="num">0.0</td><td class="num">1.0</td><td class="num">2.0</td><td class="num">5.0</td><td class="num">8.0</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Compliance &amp; support fee</td><td class="num">0.5</td><td class="num">1.0</td><td class="num">3.0</td><td class="num">3.0</td><td class="num">5.0</td></tr>
          <tr class="total"><td>Total operating revenue</td><td class="num">0.5</td><td class="num">6.9</td><td class="num">32.0</td><td class="num">41.4</td><td class="num">52.4</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Interest income</td><td class="num">0.0</td><td class="num">0.5</td><td class="num">3.5</td><td class="num">3.4</td><td class="num">3.5</td></tr>
          <tr class="total"><td>Total income</td><td class="num">0.5</td><td class="num">7.4</td><td class="num">35.4</td><td class="num">44.7</td><td class="num">55.9</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="profit">
  <div class="page">
    <div class="head"><span class="num">04</span><span class="tag">Profitability &amp; cash</span></div>
    <h2>Two years of burn, then <span class="ital moss">daylight.</span></h2>
    <p class="standfirst">
      Opex scales from $9.2M to $43.8M. EBITDA is deeply negative in 2026–27, turns
      positive in 2028, and reaches $12M by 2030. Crucially, <em>no tax is paid in any
      year</em>: $24.3M of accumulated losses (NOL) shelter all subsequent profit — the
      closing carry-forward is still $11.8M at the end of 2030.
    </p>

    <div class="two">
      <figure class="chart">
        <div class="ctitle">EBITDA &amp; Net income ($M)</div>
        <div class="cnote">Crossover to profit in 2028. Bars below the axis are losses.</div>
        <svg id="chProfit" viewBox="0 0 560 300" aria-label="EBITDA and net income"></svg>
        <div class="legend"><span><i style="background:var(--teal)"></i>EBITDA</span><span><i style="background:var(--rust)"></i>net income</span></div>
      </figure>
      <figure class="chart">
        <div class="ctitle">Closing cash balance ($M)</div>
        <div class="cnote">$100M of equity keeps cash positive throughout — trough is $9M (2026).</div>
        <svg id="chCash" viewBox="0 0 560 300" aria-label="Closing cash"></svg>
        <div class="legend"><span><i style="background:var(--moss)"></i>closing cash</span><span><i style="background:var(--rust-soft)"></i>equity raised</span></div>
      </figure>
    </div>

    <div class="callout good">
      <div class="ct">What the rebuild got right</div>
      <p>The cumulative 5-year net result is still a <strong>$11.8M deficit</strong> — the
      business is profitable on a run-rate basis by 2028 but has not yet earned back its
      losses by 2030. The model handles this honestly: tax-loss carryforward keeps cash tax
      at zero, opening cash equals prior-year close (fixing the old interest-income error),
      and the balance sheet checks to zero every year. This is the part investors won't
      argue with.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="assumptions">
  <div class="page">
    <div class="head"><span class="num">05</span><span class="tag">Assumptions to challenge</span></div>
    <h2>The numbers the diligence team will <span class="ital rust">circle.</span></h2>
    <p class="standfirst">
      The review note lists the inputs that drive the result and remain the least
      defensible. None are formula errors — they are <em>commercial</em> judgements that
      need external evidence before an investor will underwrite them.
    </p>

    <div class="tw">
      <table>
        <caption>Source: workbook <span class="mono">Notes</span> &amp; <span class="mono">Assumptions</span> tabs.</caption>
        <thead><tr><th>Assumption</th><th class="num">Model value</th><th>Reviewer concern</th><th>Priority</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Orders/month by Mar-27</td><td class="num">1,000,000</td><td>Too steep without adoption proof</td><td><span class="pill crit">critical</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td>2027 MoM growth</td><td class="num">40%</td><td>Highly aggressive compounding</td><td><span class="pill crit">critical</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td>2028 / 2029 / 2030 MoM</td><td class="num">3.0 / 2.75 / 2.5%</td><td>Still high post-ramp; needs validation</td><td><span class="pill">high</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td>AOV increase</td><td class="num">$4 → $7</td><td>Requires market justification</td><td><span class="pill">high</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Blended take rate (2027)</td><td class="num">1.375%</td><td>High for an open-infrastructure model</td><td><span class="pill crit">critical</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Onboarding cost</td><td class="num">$1–2M</td><td>Understated vs scale ambition</td><td><span class="pill">high</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tech infrastructure cost</td><td class="num">~$7M</td><td>Likely underestimated</td><td><span class="pill">high</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Mature EBITDA margin (mgmt)</td><td class="num">72%</td><td>Not credible — see note below</td><td><span class="pill fixed">re-based</span></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="ct">A note on the 70% margin</div>
      <p>The original management case implied a mature EBITDA margin around 72%. The
      <em>rebuilt</em> model in this workbook does not use that figure — it derives EBITDA
      bottom-up (revenue minus actual opex lines), landing at a far more defensible
      <strong>14–22%</strong>. So the most-cited red flag has effectively been corrected;
      the remaining exposure is the GMV ramp and take rate, which still feed the top line
      directly.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="sensitivity">
  <div class="page">
    <div class="head"><span class="num">06</span><span class="tag">Scenario view — with a defect</span></div>
    <h2>The stress test that <span class="ital rust">points the wrong way.</span></h2>
    <p class="standfirst">
      The Sensitivity tab applies multipliers to 2030 outputs for a quick downside/upside
      frame. The intent is right, but the execution has a real bug: the downside and upside
      <em>revenue</em> cells are hardcoded numbers, not formulas — and the downside value
      ($76.3M) is <em>higher</em> than the base case ($55.9M). That inverts EBITDA too, making
      the &ldquo;downside&rdquo; look better than the base. It must be refit before use.
    </p>

    <div class="tw">
      <table>
        <caption>As-published Sensitivity tab — note the inverted Revenue / EBITDA rows. Source: workbook <span class="mono">Sensitivity</span> tab.</caption>
        <thead><tr><th>2030 metric</th><th class="num">Downside</th><th class="num">Base</th><th class="num">Upside</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>GMV ($M)</td><td class="num">3,230.2</td><td class="num">4,037.8</td><td class="num">4,845.3</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Revenue ($M) <span class="pill crit">hardcoded</span></td><td class="num tneg">76.3 ⚠</td><td class="num">55.9</td><td class="num">123.7 ⚠</td></tr>
          <tr><td>EBITDA ($M) <span class="pill crit">inverted</span></td><td class="num tneg">26.0 ⚠</td><td class="num">12.1</td><td class="num">84.3</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Closing cash ($M)</td><td class="num">91.9</td><td class="num">78.4</td><td class="num">151.0</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="ct">Suggested fix</div>
      <p>Downside revenue should fall, not rise. A consistent formula —
      <span class="mono">base&nbsp;×&nbsp;GMV&nbsp;mult&nbsp;×&nbsp;take-rate&nbsp;mult</span>
      = $55.9M × 0.8 × 0.9 ≈ <strong>$40.2M</strong> downside, and × 1.2 × 1.1 ≈ <strong>$73.8M</strong>
      upside — would make the bridge directionally correct. The downside EBITDA then turns
      to roughly <strong>−$10M</strong> (opex × 1.15), which is the honest stress message: in a slow-adoption
      world, ION is loss-making again in 2030.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="analysis">
  <div class="page">
    <div class="head"><span class="num">07</span><span class="tag">Analysis &amp; verdict</span></div>
    <h2>Correct plumbing, <span class="ital">unproven pressure.</span></h2>

    <div class="two">
      <div>
        <h3 class="moss" style="font-size:21px;margin:0 0 10px">Strengths</h3>
        <ul class="clean">
          <li><strong>Internally consistent.</strong> Three statements link; balance check is zero in every year; D&amp;A rolls from a capex schedule.</li>
          <li><strong>Honest tax &amp; interest.</strong> NOL carryforward shelters early profits; interest is computed only on positive opening cash, fixing the prior linkage error.</li>
          <li><strong>Margins already re-based.</strong> EBITDA is built bottom-up at 14–22%, abandoning the non-credible 72% management figure.</li>
          <li><strong>Right cost taxonomy.</strong> Salary, onboarding, tech, network ops, promotions, media, legal — the buckets are correct; only magnitudes are in question.</li>
          <li><strong>Funded for the burn.</strong> $100M of equity keeps cash positive throughout; the trough is a comfortable $9M.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="rust" style="font-size:21px;margin:0 0 10px">Weaknesses</h3>
        <ul class="clean">
          <li><strong>One curve does all the work.</strong> 200× order growth to Mar-27 and 40% MoM through 2027 are asserted, not bridged from sellers × activation × frequency.</li>
          <li><strong>Take rate is optimistic <em>and</em> shrinking.</strong> 1.375% is high for open infrastructure, yet the model also bakes in fee compression to 0.975% — two opposing bets at once.</li>
          <li><strong>Costs likely understated.</strong> Onboarding ($1–2M) and tech infra (~$7M) look light against billion-dollar GMV ambition in Indonesia.</li>
          <li><strong>Interest income flatters earnings.</strong> Up to ~10% of total income is return on raised capital, not operations — investors will strip it out.</li>
          <li><strong>Sensitivity tab is defective.</strong> Hardcoded, inverted downside revenue makes the stress test misleading as shipped.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout" style="margin-top:30px">
      <div class="ct">Bottom line</div>
      <p>This is a <strong>technically valid model with an overstated business case</strong> —
      exactly the distinction the review note makes. The formulas are right and the outputs are
      mathematically clean, but profitability is manufactured by a GMV curve that no adoption
      evidence yet supports. To make it investor-grade: (1) rebuild GMV from MSME onboarding and
      active-seller cohorts rather than a fixed order target, (2) justify or phase the take rate,
      (3) re-cost onboarding and infrastructure on unit economics, and (4) repair the sensitivity
      tab so the downside actually reads as a downside.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

